@John ezra
I thought there must be a Scottish connection, the terms 'burgh' (buh-ruh) and 'royal burgh' were used extensively for administrative areas from the 12th century.

According to Wikipedia, Pittsburgh was named in 1758 by a Scottish general in honour of statesman William Pitt.  Pitt emphasised the American colonists right to liberty, "I rejoice that America hs resisted."

@Jane Wheelaghan

I thought the same thing. With all due respect to John Ezra's theory (and I've got kinfolk in Pittsburgh, which qualifies me to chime in here) the H would probably not have come from German, where a Burg is a city or a castle,  so the general meaning did cross over. 
The German language isn't big on extraneous final letters, though I can't claim to be an expert going back to Middle High German. But we've got Hamburg, Würzburg, Brandenburg, Magdeburg, Aschaffenburg, and even "Ein' feste Burg" (the hymn "A Mighty Fortress").

@Terry

Yes! That was some pahr ahtage! We were without power for about 60 hours, and some are just now getting it back, a week later. Lots of people seen sitting in their cars charging their phones and laptops. I said to my wife that given the lack of TV, internet, etc., there well might be a mini baby boom here in the city in ninth months!

Overall I thought Duquesne Light has been fairly responsive about getting the power back on and have no complaints -- but I'm sure other people without power would disagree.

